So let's go.

12
00:00:32,683 --> 00:00:40,046
So yeah, the great thing about GDC is we look really cool in retrospect after we spent way

13
00:00:40,086 --> 00:00:46,148
too many years making a game and trying a lot of things that didn't work.

14
00:00:47,448 --> 00:00:52,410
So I wanted to give a disclaimer that this talk makes the development of Subnautica look

15
00:00:52,610 --> 00:00:53,490
a lot easier than it was.

16
00:00:54,797 --> 00:00:58,240
It took about 5 years to make this game and it was a really

17
00:00:58,260 --> 00:01:00,742
hard development for a good portion of that.

18
00:01:02,204 --> 00:01:04,405
And our previous game actually took 8 years.

19
00:01:05,166 --> 00:01:09,770
So we're now just getting to the point where we think we know

20
00:01:09,810 --> 00:01:12,452
how to make games and our games are becoming more successful.

21
00:01:13,313 --> 00:01:17,096
And you know, I don't want this to look like it was an

22
00:01:17,156 --> 00:01:17,897
overnight success.

23
00:01:18,818 --> 00:01:20,359
There's a there's a saying that

24
00:01:21,757 --> 00:01:24,198
You know, an overnight success rarely happens overnight,

25
00:01:24,599 --> 00:01:25,719
and that's definitely true for us.

26
00:01:26,980 --> 00:01:27,880
So, let's get started.

27
00:01:29,241 --> 00:01:32,243
Before Subnautica, we spent eight years

28
00:01:32,303 --> 00:01:33,463
working on a first-person shooter,

29
00:01:33,763 --> 00:01:37,025
real-time strategy hybrid called Natural Selection 1 and 2.

30
00:01:38,766 --> 00:01:40,747
And at the end of that development,

31
00:01:41,307 --> 00:01:43,088
I was totally exhausted.

32
00:01:45,268 --> 00:01:50,111
We had a lot of guns in that game and it was a competitive online shooter.

33
00:01:50,131 --> 00:01:54,414
So people were always going on the forums and yelling at us for balance,

34
00:01:54,434 --> 00:01:56,096
you know, yelling at me basically.

35
00:01:58,532 --> 00:02:01,213
And it was just a hyper competitive game.

36
00:02:01,894 --> 00:02:03,755
And I love that stuff.

37
00:02:03,795 --> 00:02:05,496
I love the guns, I love the strategy,

38
00:02:05,576 --> 00:02:07,197
I love the tech trees,

39
00:02:07,257 --> 00:02:10,079
and intense team versus team combat.

40
00:02:10,799 --> 00:02:14,142
But I just felt like I didn't want to spend

41
00:02:14,202 --> 00:02:17,524
another section of my life adding more,

42
00:02:19,105 --> 00:02:19,985
basically doing the same thing.

43
00:02:20,005 --> 00:02:22,827
And I was feeling really burned out creatively.

44
00:02:24,763 --> 00:02:29,106
And right around that time is when we had the Sandy Hook shooting.

45
00:02:31,067 --> 00:02:33,409
And yeah, maybe you remember this picture.

46
00:02:33,429 --> 00:02:35,511
I definitely remember it.

47
00:02:37,072 --> 00:02:42,496
And of course, we've had so many mass shootings since that time, and now we have the Christchurch

48
00:02:42,596 --> 00:02:43,476
one, not even a week old.

49
00:02:44,237 --> 00:02:45,458
You can't even keep track of them anymore.

50
00:02:46,910 --> 00:02:51,255
And I just didn't want to add more guns to a game, or to the world.

51
00:02:51,935 --> 00:02:58,061
Even if they're virtual guns, even if I believe that virtual violence does not create real

52
00:02:58,101 --> 00:03:02,085
violence, which I do believe that that's not true, but I just didn't want to spend more

53
00:03:02,105 --> 00:03:02,666
time doing that.

54
00:03:03,366 --> 00:03:05,829
And that's where the original idea of Subnautica came from.

55
00:03:10,017 --> 00:03:11,758
We were also really inspired by Minecraft.

56
00:03:12,679 --> 00:03:16,641
So to me, the idea of making an open game,

57
00:03:17,021 --> 00:03:18,622
something more sandboxy,

58
00:03:19,383 --> 00:03:22,084
something where the designers and the developers

59
00:03:22,144 --> 00:03:23,705
didn't push you down one path.

60
00:03:24,345 --> 00:03:26,186
We see that a lot in AAA games

61
00:03:26,767 --> 00:03:28,988
where there's pretty much one way to play the game.

62
00:03:30,569 --> 00:03:34,531
And any kind of surprises in the game were pre-designed

63
00:03:34,831 --> 00:03:37,193
and you're just pretty much going along down the line.

64
00:03:38,221 --> 00:03:40,562
So Minecraft showed this new way to build a game,

65
00:03:42,403 --> 00:03:46,405
you know, expansive with player stories and player creation.

66
00:03:46,725 --> 00:03:48,586
And I was thinking, oh, we should,

67
00:03:48,926 --> 00:03:49,947
we can make a game like Minecraft,

68
00:03:49,967 --> 00:03:50,827
but we can do it underwater.

69
00:03:53,593 --> 00:03:58,875
We also got inspired by Clay, the makers of Don't Starve and Oxygen Not Included, Invisible

70
00:03:58,955 --> 00:03:59,876
Ink among others.

71
00:04:01,096 --> 00:04:06,218
And Clay, the thing I love about Clay is that every game they make is a different genre.

72
00:04:07,158 --> 00:04:08,419
So they never repeat themselves.

73
00:04:09,439 --> 00:04:13,281
And there's a few members on our team, including myself, that really got inspired by that.

74
00:04:13,301 --> 00:04:15,542
So we wanted to try something completely different.

75
00:04:16,740 --> 00:04:19,902
So we had this nonviolent idea, player has no guns,

76
00:04:20,563 --> 00:04:23,005
though truthfully there is violence in the game,

77
00:04:23,185 --> 00:04:25,826
it's just of course the creatures are attacking you

78
00:04:26,147 --> 00:04:27,608
and then you basically can't do anything about it.

79
00:04:29,429 --> 00:04:32,831
So yeah, you're definitely not at the top of the food chain.

80
00:04:34,132 --> 00:04:36,253
So that's the background of why we made the game.

81
00:04:36,954 --> 00:04:38,635
And I just wanna talk a little bit about

82
00:04:39,856 --> 00:04:41,076
how we built it, just briefly.

83
00:04:42,744 --> 00:04:45,346
We started development on it in early 2013.

84
00:04:45,827 --> 00:04:48,549
It came out in early access in late 2014,

85
00:04:48,890 --> 00:04:50,752
so it's almost two years.

86
00:04:51,913 --> 00:04:53,915
We had a $3 million budget, roughly.

87
00:04:55,244 --> 00:04:56,825
and that was all the money that we had earned

88
00:04:57,205 --> 00:04:58,966
from our previous game, Natural Selection 2.

89
00:05:00,728 --> 00:05:03,890
And we spent about four years in early access,

90
00:05:04,751 --> 00:05:08,634
and we released 30 or so headliner updates.

91
00:05:09,234 --> 00:05:11,316
And these headliners are the concept

92
00:05:11,376 --> 00:05:14,298
is where you build an update around one feature,

93
00:05:14,758 --> 00:05:16,219
and that feature is really marketable,

94
00:05:16,920 --> 00:05:19,722
and it's appealing, and you make a video, you make a website,

95
00:05:20,042 --> 00:05:22,004
and it was a way for us to draw attention to the game.

96
00:05:23,174 --> 00:05:26,737
because we're not known in this area at all.

97
00:05:28,539 --> 00:05:31,261
If you want to know more about how we did

98
00:05:31,281 --> 00:05:33,523
this early access development, Jonas, who's here,

99
00:05:34,224 --> 00:05:36,466
he gave a great talk yesterday, I've heard it was amazing,

100
00:05:37,287 --> 00:05:40,430
a talk called Subnautica Postmortem, yep,

101
00:05:40,890 --> 00:05:42,071
and it'll be available on the Vault,

102
00:05:42,431 --> 00:05:44,934
so if you want to hear about early access, go watch that.

103
00:05:45,594 --> 00:05:46,735
I'm not gonna talk much about it,

104
00:05:46,996 --> 00:05:49,338
I'm just gonna say one more thing, which is...

105
00:05:50,339 --> 00:05:54,122
I guess that we, let's see, yeah, we spent three million

106
00:05:54,142 --> 00:05:57,205
to get it to early access, and then another seven after that,

107
00:05:57,686 --> 00:06:00,689
which was all funded from the headliner updates

108
00:06:00,709 --> 00:06:02,891
from players buying the game, which was incredible.

109
00:06:03,091 --> 00:06:04,813
It was a wonderful rollercoaster ride.

110
00:06:05,714 --> 00:06:08,056
And our players ended up by showing us

111
00:06:09,177 --> 00:06:10,539
what the game really needed to be.

112
00:06:11,759 --> 00:06:17,881
And to date, we've sold about four million and counting units on PC, Steam, Xbox One,

113
00:06:18,261 --> 00:06:20,481
PS4, just launched on PS4.

114
00:06:21,081 --> 00:06:22,222
So it's done super well.

115
00:06:22,302 --> 00:06:24,302
We feel extremely grateful and lucky.

116
00:06:25,763 --> 00:06:29,824
So this talk is about making original games, not about all that business stuff.

117
00:06:30,924 --> 00:06:35,765
When I talk about original games, what I really want to talk about is this idea of making

118
00:06:35,805 --> 00:06:37,185
a game that's never been seen before.

119
00:06:38,183 --> 00:06:41,245
You can make a sequel, sequels can be original

120
00:06:41,325 --> 00:06:44,287
by my definition, but I want to talk about

121
00:06:44,307 --> 00:06:46,068
making something that is unique enough

122
00:06:46,148 --> 00:06:47,548
that you don't have a model to look at.

123
00:06:48,369 --> 00:06:50,530
So this illustration shows, you know,

124
00:06:50,630 --> 00:06:54,172
maybe when you start the game you have an idea

125
00:06:55,032 --> 00:06:57,874
and you think you see something that you want in your mind.

126
00:06:58,394 --> 00:07:00,395
And that's way off there in the jungle,

127
00:07:00,675 --> 00:07:01,836
off to the right, three o'clock.

128
00:07:02,857 --> 00:07:08,301
You have all sorts of assumptions about what the game will be, you have dreams and hopes

129
00:07:08,341 --> 00:07:08,861
and desires.

130
00:07:09,301 --> 00:07:14,345
And you start building the game and you're kind of going along that line and you start

131
00:07:14,365 --> 00:07:14,865
to get lost.

132
00:07:15,930 --> 00:07:18,631
And your players, maybe if you have them,

133
00:07:18,852 --> 00:07:20,632
they're saying, do this, do that.

134
00:07:20,972 --> 00:07:21,873
What is this game really about?

135
00:07:21,973 --> 00:07:23,033
I want more of this, more of that.

136
00:07:23,913 --> 00:07:27,435
And that can be a really desperate, terrible place

137
00:07:27,475 --> 00:07:30,596
to be in because you still don't know what your game is.

138
00:07:30,836 --> 00:07:32,116
How can you possibly know what it is?

139
00:07:32,457 --> 00:07:33,797
How can you take feedback if you don't know

140
00:07:34,337 --> 00:07:35,158
really what you're building?

141
00:07:36,300 --> 00:07:41,762
So, eventually, I mean, so this talk is about how to get through that jungle.

142
00:07:42,362 --> 00:07:47,564
If there's one thing I hope that you have a takeaway from, it's less about the design

143
00:07:47,584 --> 00:07:50,165
of Subnautica and more about how to find your own way through the jungle.

144
00:07:50,185 --> 00:07:54,347
And I'm going to show you how we did it, and I hope to tie it into a larger framework that

145
00:07:54,407 --> 00:07:55,427
you can use for your own games.

146
00:07:57,779 --> 00:08:01,783
Okay, Jesse Schell wrote a book called

147
00:08:03,244 --> 00:08:06,327
The Art of Game Design, Game Design Lenses,

148
00:08:06,487 --> 00:08:09,711
a book of lenses, and in it he talks about

149
00:08:09,871 --> 00:08:14,836
using lenses as a tool, as a way to look at

150
00:08:15,016 --> 00:08:15,917
one aspect of your game.

151
00:08:16,758 --> 00:08:19,621
So for instance, he might talk about the lens of skill.

152
00:08:20,462 --> 00:08:24,145
So if you look through that lens of skill and you look at every aspect of your game

153
00:08:24,926 --> 00:08:27,128
and you say, how much skill does this level require?

154
00:08:27,208 --> 00:08:29,590
How much does this one? Is this too easy? Too hard?

155
00:08:29,950 --> 00:08:32,913
You can start to get insight about just skill in your game.

156
00:08:33,674 --> 00:08:36,796
But that's useful because if you just think about your game in terms of fun,

157
00:08:37,277 --> 00:08:39,979
that's super generic and it's not very helpful to anyone.

158
00:08:40,600 --> 00:08:43,723
So he talks about, here's how you do the lens of chance.

159
00:08:43,963 --> 00:08:45,825
Here's how you do the lens of accessibility.

160
00:08:46,606 --> 00:08:49,269
And to me, one of the most important ones

161
00:08:49,609 --> 00:08:50,570
is the lens of emotion.

162
00:08:52,593 --> 00:08:56,337
Genova Chen of that game company talks a lot about designing

163
00:08:56,377 --> 00:08:57,578
games with emotion first.

164
00:08:58,544 --> 00:09:02,426
And to me, that's really about that lens of emotion.

165
00:09:02,786 --> 00:09:04,827
You have to figure out what emotions your players,

166
00:09:05,387 --> 00:09:06,908
what emotions you want them to feel.

167
00:09:07,488 --> 00:09:09,489
Then you notice what emotions they are feeling,

168
00:09:09,869 --> 00:09:11,530
and then you want to figure out how to get them

169
00:09:11,650 --> 00:09:13,471
from where they are to where you want them to be.

170
00:09:14,892 --> 00:09:17,853
So I think this lens of emotion is where,

171
00:09:18,053 --> 00:09:19,934
I mean, this is where we started with Subnautica,

172
00:09:20,014 --> 00:09:21,295
and I think it was probably

173
00:09:21,335 --> 00:09:22,815
the most important decision we ever made.

174
00:09:24,794 --> 00:09:30,899
A lot of design talks talk about pillars, design pillars, and I'm not going to give

175
00:09:31,700 --> 00:09:36,124
much information on design pillars, because, well, I'll give a summary, because some people

176
00:09:36,164 --> 00:09:36,524
may not know.

177
00:09:36,544 --> 00:09:44,632
A pillar is where you create a concept of usually a feature or a set of mechanics around

178
00:09:44,652 --> 00:09:44,972
your game.

179
00:09:45,850 --> 00:09:47,091
and you have a couple of those pillars,

180
00:09:47,911 --> 00:09:51,412
and those, you choose that at the beginning of your game,

181
00:09:52,012 --> 00:09:53,772
and that guides the development of your game

182
00:09:54,152 --> 00:09:55,853
for all of eternity, basically.

183
00:09:56,613 --> 00:09:58,853
So I am a big fan of design pillars.

184
00:09:59,073 --> 00:10:00,514
We've used them in every game.

185
00:10:01,294 --> 00:10:05,055
But if we apply the lens of emotion to a design pillar,

186
00:10:05,175 --> 00:10:06,495
I think they get a lot more powerful.

187
00:10:07,886 --> 00:10:09,547
and a lot more important and relevant.

188
00:10:10,007 --> 00:10:12,048
So right here, this is, here are the first,

189
00:10:12,368 --> 00:10:13,669
they're the only three pillars

190
00:10:13,849 --> 00:10:15,070
that we ever had for Subnautica.

191
00:10:15,830 --> 00:10:17,371
And this is actually a screenshot

192
00:10:17,431 --> 00:10:20,493
of the very first document ever written about the game.

193
00:10:21,473 --> 00:10:25,095
And you can see the first one is Vessel Design Building,

194
00:10:25,495 --> 00:10:27,936
and that's kind of like a gameplay system.

195
00:10:28,757 --> 00:10:31,798
And then to the right, in parentheses, Intoxicating Creation.

196
00:10:32,819 --> 00:10:35,700
So why do we have Vessel Design and Building?

197
00:10:37,272 --> 00:10:41,793
The reason is because we want players to have the feeling of intoxicating creation, so I

198
00:10:41,833 --> 00:10:41,993
say.

199
00:10:42,013 --> 00:10:44,774
Okay, we have three pillars here.

200
00:10:44,794 --> 00:10:48,735
I won't go through all of them because we actually only focused on one of them.

201
00:10:49,795 --> 00:10:51,075
So we thought we were going to do three.

202
00:10:51,095 --> 00:10:56,757
We ended up by doing one, and we thought that would be exploration and discovery, you know,

203
00:10:56,837 --> 00:10:59,638
parentheses the thrill of the unknown, the why.

204
00:11:01,408 --> 00:11:03,149
and we actually focused only on that.

205
00:11:03,729 --> 00:11:07,211
The other stuff came in in a secondary way,

206
00:11:08,112 --> 00:11:09,632
but I think that's actually one of the reasons

207
00:11:09,673 --> 00:11:10,393
why it works so well.

208
00:11:11,594 --> 00:11:14,135
So, starting with emotion, thrill of the unknown.

209
00:11:15,355 --> 00:11:18,496
The first thing we did was started with the music.

210
00:11:19,017 --> 00:11:20,317
And this is how I like to work.

211
00:11:20,857 --> 00:11:22,498
Just because it's about Subnautica,

212
00:11:22,518 --> 00:11:23,418
I thought I would show it to you.

213
00:11:23,898 --> 00:11:24,718
And it's about the emotion.

214
00:11:24,939 --> 00:11:31,241
So the first prototype was just a menu with a song,

215
00:11:31,781 --> 00:11:32,441
which you can hear right now.

216
00:11:55,012 --> 00:11:59,696
So I don't know about you, but when I heard this, I mean I went through so many different

217
00:11:59,796 --> 00:12:04,560
artists and I tried to find something that was evoking the idea of the feelings we wanted

218
00:12:04,580 --> 00:12:05,381
to create with this game.

219
00:12:06,181 --> 00:12:09,925
I mean I feel like I'm underwater already, it's just one track of music.

220
00:12:10,816 --> 00:12:19,478
This is Solar Fields and it is shamelessly stolen and never published anywhere so I think it's okay.

221
00:12:19,518 --> 00:12:24,839
You can even hear like a little like I don't know radio signals or something in the background.

222
00:12:25,359 --> 00:12:28,660
I don't know I've never really played this for anyone else so I don't really know if you guys

223
00:12:28,700 --> 00:12:34,901
feel it but that's what I feel. So that was how we started with that emotion and whenever I needed

224
00:12:34,921 --> 00:12:40,082
to I could just go back to that and think you know to reconnect with what the point of this game is.

225
00:12:41,623 --> 00:12:44,565
So after that musical exploration,

226
00:12:44,685 --> 00:12:47,367
starting with the emotion, we ended up

227
00:12:47,407 --> 00:12:50,749
by building our first prototype, real playable prototype.

228
00:12:51,309 --> 00:12:53,231
And I want to give a little background on something popular

229
00:12:53,331 --> 00:12:58,154
here in Silicon Valley called the Minimum Viable Product,

230
00:12:58,534 --> 00:12:59,274
the MVP.

231
00:13:01,115 --> 00:13:06,018
So if you're making a car, it's really hard to go make a car,

232
00:13:06,218 --> 00:13:08,140
because a lot of times you don't know that you're making a car.

233
00:13:09,052 --> 00:13:11,634
So you, instead of building a car,

234
00:13:11,854 --> 00:13:13,135
you start with a skateboard.

235
00:13:13,595 --> 00:13:15,197
Something that serves the same purpose,

236
00:13:15,277 --> 00:13:18,179
it's transportation and it will get you where you need to go,

237
00:13:18,820 --> 00:13:20,321
but it doesn't have all the bells and whistles

238
00:13:20,501 --> 00:13:22,282
or the technical complexity of building a car.

239
00:13:22,663 --> 00:13:25,165
And plus you don't really know you want a car yet,

240
00:13:25,305 --> 00:13:26,246
you just know you want something

241
00:13:26,266 --> 00:13:27,587
that gets you from point A to point B.

242
00:13:28,467 --> 00:13:29,489
So you release a skateboard.

243
00:13:30,690 --> 00:13:32,333
You can see the unhappy face.

244
00:13:32,693 --> 00:13:34,155
Like users are like,

245
00:13:34,576 --> 00:13:36,759
it's just a skateboard and it's not that great.

246
00:13:37,860 --> 00:13:39,382
