504
00:25:07,767 --> 00:25:09,189
they turn around and they come home

505
00:25:09,209 --> 00:25:09,910
because it's really boring.

506
00:25:12,215 --> 00:25:19,258
And then here is you can see the same map with the height data and you can see if you know what the Aurora looks like.

507
00:25:19,378 --> 00:25:23,580
It's around four o'clock, it's that big kind of oval shape, the crashed spaceship.

508
00:25:26,021 --> 00:25:30,803
So when the game starts we choose a random start location and that's that green area in the middle.

509
00:25:31,643 --> 00:25:34,324
And the cool thing about this random start is that...

510
00:25:35,045 --> 00:25:38,449
people actually thought that our world was procedurally generated.

511
00:25:38,930 --> 00:25:41,693
Many players thought that, which was a huge win for us

512
00:25:41,773 --> 00:25:43,555
because they felt like they could replay the game,

513
00:25:43,595 --> 00:25:45,377
and they probably could replay it a little bit,

514
00:25:45,478 --> 00:25:46,759
like, you know, maybe a couple times.

515
00:25:48,942 --> 00:25:50,404
But it added to that feeling of mystery.

516
00:25:51,569 --> 00:25:54,471
So let's see, they start there randomly,

517
00:25:54,691 --> 00:25:57,353
and you can see that's the side view of the height map,

518
00:25:57,674 --> 00:25:59,495
and the green is where they spawn.

519
00:26:00,156 --> 00:26:01,717
And what we ended up by doing is putting,

520
00:26:02,097 --> 00:26:04,599
just basically making the map almost like a pyramid.

521
00:26:05,240 --> 00:26:06,321
So you start at the top,

522
00:26:06,461 --> 00:26:08,082
and of course you have the water up here.

523
00:26:08,743 --> 00:26:11,725
And as you swim out, as you explore in any direction,

524
00:26:11,785 --> 00:26:14,187
you're just gonna naturally follow the line down.

525
00:26:15,028 --> 00:26:18,973
So this meant that, and we tried other approaches too,

526
00:26:19,033 --> 00:26:21,575
but this one ended up by having players

527
00:26:21,856 --> 00:26:23,898
just go where we wanted them to,

528
00:26:24,058 --> 00:26:25,880
basically go to the interesting stuff

529
00:26:25,981 --> 00:26:27,102
and follow the world down.

530
00:26:30,484 --> 00:26:32,306
And then of course we did put all this other,

531
00:26:32,326 --> 00:26:33,988
the ghost leviathans out there too,

532
00:26:34,028 --> 00:26:34,889
which I already mentioned.

533
00:26:35,690 --> 00:26:37,492
Okay.

534
00:26:37,512 --> 00:26:42,138
So, another huge kind of reframe for us in this game

535
00:26:42,839 --> 00:26:46,062
was this idea of never telling the player what to do

536
00:26:46,703 --> 00:26:48,065
and respecting the player's time.

537
00:26:48,805 --> 00:26:52,270
And this ties into the idea of an intrinsic reward,

538
00:26:52,290 --> 00:26:54,573
you know, intrinsic over extrinsic rewards.

539
00:26:55,574 --> 00:26:59,239
So Jamie Chang and Chris Hecker both wrote excellent articles

540
00:26:59,319 --> 00:27:01,802
on this subject, and they really inspired us

541
00:27:01,883 --> 00:27:04,246
and got us to the next level with our game.

542
00:27:05,147 --> 00:27:11,490
So an extrinsic reward is something you probably are familiar with, like gamer rank, achievements,

543
00:27:11,710 --> 00:27:17,474
leveling up, you know, gold. It's like, you know, tangible specific rewards that are given to you

544
00:27:17,514 --> 00:27:18,555
when you do the right thing.

545
00:27:19,717 --> 00:27:24,019
An intrinsic reward is like maybe a positive emotion,

546
00:27:24,039 --> 00:27:27,140
or maybe like you feel good when you play the game,

547
00:27:27,840 --> 00:27:29,501
or you enjoy spending time with your friends,

548
00:27:29,601 --> 00:27:30,741
so that's why you play the game.

549
00:27:31,802 --> 00:27:33,703
If you're motivated by an intrinsic reward,

550
00:27:34,283 --> 00:27:36,484
I like to think that you're having

551
00:27:36,524 --> 00:27:38,524
a more meaningful interaction with the game.

552
00:27:39,725 --> 00:27:42,786
And I was really hoping that we could fully embrace

553
00:27:44,107 --> 00:27:45,347
100% intrinsic rewards in this game.

554
00:27:46,413 --> 00:27:51,676
It's a little scary because, you know, we've all been taught as designers that extrinsic

555
00:27:51,716 --> 00:27:54,498
rewards drive player behavior and motivation.

556
00:27:55,098 --> 00:27:58,800
And there have been a lot of studies on this, and they do drive it in the short term.

557
00:27:58,820 --> 00:28:00,981
I mean, you should definitely read these papers.

558
00:28:01,001 --> 00:28:03,243
It's all in the appendix if you want to dive deeper on this.

559
00:28:03,303 --> 00:28:04,263
I won't summarize it here.

560
00:28:05,124 --> 00:28:07,765
but it does drive player motivation in the short term

561
00:28:08,125 --> 00:28:09,986
and it drops it in the long term.

562
00:28:10,426 --> 00:28:12,667
That's the summary, it's not fully accurate,

563
00:28:12,707 --> 00:28:14,748
but let's just say it's largely accurate.

564
00:28:15,448 --> 00:28:17,069
So we wanted players to play the game

565
00:28:17,109 --> 00:28:18,130
because they love the game,

566
00:28:18,150 --> 00:28:21,151
and we were willing to take a risk

567
00:28:21,551 --> 00:28:23,312
and not handhold them

568
00:28:23,472 --> 00:28:25,573
and not give them quests along the way.

569
00:28:26,214 --> 00:28:27,074
We didn't want them to feel like

570
00:28:27,094 --> 00:28:28,375
they were tricked into playing the game.

571
00:28:31,375 --> 00:28:37,420
So one of those, one of the ideas there was we had to start thinking about, like, instead

572
00:28:37,460 --> 00:28:43,546
of tutorials or helping players learn the game, we had to flip that idea on its head

573
00:28:43,706 --> 00:28:47,430
and realize that when players discover the game, that's actually the fun part.

574
00:28:48,567 --> 00:28:53,213
So, you know, coming back to this pillar emotion,

575
00:28:54,394 --> 00:28:56,917
you know, the thrill of the unknown,

576
00:28:56,937 --> 00:29:00,321
it just goes away once it becomes known, right?

577
00:29:00,381 --> 00:29:02,263
Like, it's like the horror,

578
00:29:02,403 --> 00:29:04,145
like the monster in a horror movie.

579
00:29:04,466 --> 00:29:06,228
As soon as you see it, the thrill goes away.

580
00:29:07,089 --> 00:29:09,310
So we definitely didn't want to just tell people things.

581
00:29:10,490 --> 00:29:12,091
It was okay if they discovered it on their own,

582
00:29:12,591 --> 00:29:14,412
but we were never going to just explain it to them.

583
00:29:15,152 --> 00:29:17,553
So this is the idea of this mantra that we had,

584
00:29:17,573 --> 00:29:20,155
at least I would basically yell at other people

585
00:29:20,195 --> 00:29:21,575
and tell them, never tell the player what to do.

586
00:29:21,835 --> 00:29:22,676
You're telling the player what to do.

587
00:29:24,817 --> 00:29:27,978
And this idea of not feeling bad

588
00:29:28,118 --> 00:29:29,459
if players have to go to the wiki.

589
00:29:30,179 --> 00:29:32,521
And that was something that kind of crippled us early on.

590
00:29:32,561 --> 00:29:34,541
We're like, oh, but what if players have to go to the wiki

591
00:29:34,601 --> 00:29:35,802
because we didn't explain something.

592
00:29:36,705 --> 00:29:39,428
Well, Minecraft did it and it was amazing.

593
00:29:40,049 --> 00:29:43,392
So we realized that that learning is by far,

594
00:29:43,792 --> 00:29:45,414
like that learning is actually the fun part.

595
00:29:45,874 --> 00:29:47,235
So as long as players are learning,

596
00:29:47,496 --> 00:29:49,958
I mean it's still not great if they have to go to the wiki,

597
00:29:50,038 --> 00:29:51,379
you'd rather have them learn in game.

598
00:29:51,860 --> 00:29:53,281
But as long as they're the ones learning

599
00:29:53,481 --> 00:29:54,583
and we're not just telling them,

600
00:29:55,043 --> 00:29:56,705
that's by far more important.

601
00:29:58,878 --> 00:30:02,621
And a corollary is that the more frustration

602
00:30:02,701 --> 00:30:05,383
players would have, the more exhilarated they would be

603
00:30:05,423 --> 00:30:06,984
when they finally overcame the obstacle.

604
00:30:07,705 --> 00:30:10,367
So we had to change how we thought about frustration.

605
00:30:10,567 --> 00:30:11,888
It wasn't just necessarily bad

606
00:30:11,928 --> 00:30:13,109
as soon as players were frustrated.

607
00:30:13,129 --> 00:30:14,670
It's like, well, actually, this could be good

608
00:30:14,911 --> 00:30:16,051
as long as they don't stop playing.

609
00:30:16,071 --> 00:30:18,673
If they stop playing, then you know it's bad.

610
00:30:19,034 --> 00:30:22,096
We actually put some telemetrics in there

611
00:30:22,176 --> 00:30:25,579
to get a better example of that, to know more about that.

612
00:30:28,238 --> 00:30:30,119
Okay, let's see here.

613
00:30:30,639 --> 00:30:32,700
Checking my time.

614
00:30:35,201 --> 00:30:37,642
Another technique we used a couple times in the game

615
00:30:37,662 --> 00:30:39,103
and I would like to continue to use more

616
00:30:39,383 --> 00:30:45,025
is this concept of training wheels.

617
00:30:45,805 --> 00:30:47,526
When we first released into early access,

618
00:30:47,906 --> 00:30:49,867
we didn't have any survival mechanics.

619
00:30:50,267 --> 00:30:53,008
We had no hunger, no eating or drinking.

620
00:30:53,982 --> 00:30:54,824
and our players were like,

621
00:30:54,844 --> 00:30:56,406
ah, how can you make a survival game

622
00:30:56,446 --> 00:30:58,750
without, you know, hunger and thirst?

623
00:30:59,051 --> 00:31:00,713
And we didn't even know we were making a survival game,

624
00:31:00,773 --> 00:31:02,336
but someone tagged it on Steam,

625
00:31:02,556 --> 00:31:03,478
so they said it was a survival game.

626
00:31:04,310 --> 00:31:07,613
So they convinced us to put the hunger and thirst in.

627
00:31:08,574 --> 00:31:10,916
And the really cool thing about it, something, again,

628
00:31:10,936 --> 00:31:13,378
this talk is all about how we just stumbled

629
00:31:13,478 --> 00:31:16,581
on the good stuff, but it's noticing the good stuff.

630
00:31:18,443 --> 00:31:22,026
We noticed that players, early on in the game,

631
00:31:22,166 --> 00:31:23,848
because we had no direct goals,

632
00:31:24,749 --> 00:31:28,772
they understood that they needed to eat and drink immediately,

633
00:31:28,972 --> 00:31:30,153
because if they didn't, they would die.

634
00:31:30,754 --> 00:31:33,716
So early on in the game, they would go out, find fish,

635
00:31:34,196 --> 00:31:35,918
get water, come back, cook it, eat it.

636
00:31:35,938 --> 00:31:37,980
And then they have some time where

637
00:31:38,000 --> 00:31:39,541
they can just kind of explore interfaces

638
00:31:39,581 --> 00:31:40,802
or just kind of go out on their own.

639
00:31:41,202 --> 00:31:44,125
Then a little indicator pops up again and says, oh, you're

640
00:31:44,165 --> 00:31:44,765
running out of food.

641
00:31:45,206 --> 00:31:45,686
They go back.

642
00:31:46,507 --> 00:31:50,390
Over time, as they learned how to master their calories

643
00:31:50,530 --> 00:31:53,132
and water, like most survival games,

644
00:31:53,652 --> 00:31:54,673
it gets easier and easier.

645
00:31:55,594 --> 00:32:00,157
So it kind of like falls away.

646
00:32:00,777 --> 00:32:02,399
You don't have to think about it anymore.

647
00:32:02,479 --> 00:32:03,219
You start farming.

648
00:32:03,660 --> 00:32:06,041
You have machinery that's cranking out water for you.

649
00:32:06,462 --> 00:32:08,623
So this whole kind of like motivation

650
00:32:08,703 --> 00:32:10,305
of telling you what to do early on,

651
00:32:10,765 --> 00:32:13,447
it just kind of slipped away like training wheels.

652
00:32:14,520 --> 00:32:16,501
which to me was the perfect solution

653
00:32:16,641 --> 00:32:18,342
because we wanted players to come up with their own goals.

654
00:32:19,443 --> 00:32:20,963
But we didn't want them to feel aimless in the beginning.

655
00:32:22,204 --> 00:32:23,985
Another way we use this concept of training wheels

656
00:32:24,625 --> 00:32:25,845
is through our crafting menu.

657
00:32:26,846 --> 00:32:28,487
So in the beginning,

658
00:32:30,047 --> 00:32:32,468
like, you know, we were heavily inspired by Don't Starve,

659
00:32:32,829 --> 00:32:33,429
their crafting.

660
00:32:34,489 --> 00:32:35,690
We have a similar crafting menu.

661
00:32:37,110 --> 00:32:38,931
But in the beginning, we only give you a few options.

662
00:32:39,351 --> 00:32:41,592
I mean, I can't remember how many are there at the start,

663
00:32:41,712 --> 00:32:43,153
but there's only a few relevant ones.

664
00:32:44,114 --> 00:32:47,355
And over time, we add many, many more options

665
00:32:47,475 --> 00:32:49,276
and even entire new menus.

666
00:32:49,776 --> 00:32:51,376
So you have the fabricator menu to start.

667
00:32:51,617 --> 00:32:52,657
That expands and expands.

668
00:32:52,697 --> 00:32:54,358
And then we added like five other menus

669
00:32:54,398 --> 00:32:55,198
over the course of the game.

670
00:32:55,798 --> 00:32:58,099
But in the beginning, the stuff that we really want you to do

671
00:32:58,119 --> 00:32:59,240
is get loot.

672
00:33:01,060 --> 00:33:03,922
And if you craft one of the only options there,

673
00:33:04,062 --> 00:33:06,944
which is like the O2 tank or the fins,

674
00:33:07,745 --> 00:33:11,287
then that kind of promotes a get loot style of game,

675
00:33:11,427 --> 00:33:12,187
you know, of gameplay.

676
00:33:13,188 --> 00:33:15,189
Or, you know, we wanted you to fix that radio,

677
00:33:15,249 --> 00:33:17,311
which was there in your escape pod.

678
00:33:17,851 --> 00:33:19,592
That kind of kicks off one of the storylines.

679
00:33:20,273 --> 00:33:22,954
So instead of telling you, like, go fix the radio,

680
00:33:23,094 --> 00:33:25,836
we just put as one of the only options, a little repair tool.

681
00:33:25,916 --> 00:33:27,377
And guess what, there's only one thing you can repair

682
00:33:27,497 --> 00:33:28,878
that you can know about when you start the game,

683
00:33:28,898 --> 00:33:29,518
and that's the radio.

684
00:33:31,483 --> 00:33:33,291
And then we have pipes and air pumps,

685
00:33:33,893 --> 00:33:36,324
and those kind of encourage you to build a mini-base.

686
00:33:37,650 --> 00:33:40,031
So those are kind of more of our directed goals.

687
00:33:40,431 --> 00:33:42,352
These are things that we wanted the player to do.

688
00:33:42,452 --> 00:33:43,952
We knew it was good for the early game.

689
00:33:43,992 --> 00:33:46,533
It helped players get comfortable, get on their feet.

690
00:33:49,114 --> 00:33:52,636
But we didn't want to control them the whole game.

691
00:33:52,656 --> 00:33:54,236
We wanted them to start coming up with their own goals.

692
00:33:54,776 --> 00:33:57,017
So over time, we added many more options.

693
00:33:57,617 --> 00:34:00,419
And what's happening is the menu is getting more,

694
00:34:00,659 --> 00:34:01,379
because it's getting bigger,

695
00:34:02,160 --> 00:34:08,588
Like the and it's being populated by player choices essentially by scanning fact fragments and things

696
00:34:09,870 --> 00:34:15,437
We have less and less control over that. So as this expands these other goals, they tend to be more player driven

697
00:34:16,553 --> 00:34:19,294
So we have a high capacity O2 tank that lets you go deeper.

698
00:34:19,314 --> 00:34:20,515
We have a radiation suit.

699
00:34:21,095 --> 00:34:22,596
Oh, you see the radiation suit.

700
00:34:22,656 --> 00:34:25,117
Maybe I'll go, maybe I can get through that radiation now

701
00:34:25,177 --> 00:34:25,837
next to the Aurora.

702
00:34:25,857 --> 00:34:27,418
Ah, maybe I can board the Aurora.

703
00:34:27,778 --> 00:34:31,219
But the players feel like they created that goal themselves.

704
00:34:31,440 --> 00:34:33,961
And they more or less did, but we influenced it.

705
00:34:35,801 --> 00:34:36,902
Then we have a pathfinder tool.

706
00:34:37,222 --> 00:34:38,543
Oh, maybe I should explore some caves.

707
00:34:40,256 --> 00:34:42,957
air bladder, maybe I can explore some deep open areas

708
00:34:43,057 --> 00:34:44,858
because the thing lets you come back up really fast,

709
00:34:44,958 --> 00:34:47,179
so you can go straight down, use all your oxygen,

710
00:34:47,199 --> 00:34:48,260
then pop straight back up.

711
00:34:49,400 --> 00:34:51,781
Or the laser cutter, maybe I can go explore wrecks.

712
00:34:52,582 --> 00:34:57,124
So this is a way that we can kind of guide players,

713
00:34:57,424 --> 00:35:00,765
but kind of do it invisibly and have that control,

714
00:35:01,126 --> 00:35:03,307
that guide kind of go away over time.

715
00:35:07,347 --> 00:35:13,653
Okay, a lot of people have talked about the story in Subnautica and how it's structured

716
00:35:13,733 --> 00:35:16,675
and how they had a different experience than someone else.

717
00:35:17,156 --> 00:35:23,442
That makes us super happy and I would say that we pretty much organically fell into

718
00:35:23,482 --> 00:35:24,002
this approach.

719
00:35:24,883 --> 00:35:28,687
And the way we did it was most games would have a linear story or no story.

720
00:35:29,667 --> 00:35:32,789
And what we did is we had multi, multi-linear stories,

721
00:35:33,169 --> 00:35:34,690
like seven different stories.

722
00:35:35,130 --> 00:35:38,071
So the first one, this is the Aurora storyline.

723
00:35:38,552 --> 00:35:40,733
So the explorer find the exosuit, the prawn,

724
00:35:40,873 --> 00:35:41,793
and find blue tablet.

725
00:35:42,594 --> 00:35:44,515
That one kicks off at a random time.

726
00:35:45,315 --> 00:35:47,376
So this is, you know, left to right is time,

727
00:35:48,036 --> 00:35:49,997
and the gray box is what the thing

728
00:35:50,037 --> 00:35:52,218
that triggers the beginning of the storyline.

729
00:35:53,297 --> 00:35:55,579
So then we have another one, Sunbeam Story.

730
00:35:56,019 --> 00:35:58,040
When you repair the radio, that one kicks off.

731
00:35:58,580 --> 00:36:01,242
So whenever possible, we had storylines

732
00:36:01,602 --> 00:36:03,083
kick off by player action.

733
00:36:03,984 --> 00:36:05,304
Sometimes we have random timers,

734
00:36:05,404 --> 00:36:06,945
but either way there's variance there,

735
00:36:06,965 --> 00:36:08,166
and that's what's the most important.

736
00:36:09,447 --> 00:36:11,968
We have the Degasi Story, or Visit the Floating Island,

737
00:36:12,008 --> 00:36:13,609
I think that one, that's what it was.

738
00:36:14,090 --> 00:36:16,231
Escape pods, when you find the first escape pod.

739
00:36:17,476 --> 00:36:19,796
the infection story, the precursor story,

740
00:36:20,817 --> 00:36:21,657
and the emperor story.

741
00:36:22,237 --> 00:36:23,697
So the thing that's really cool about this

742
00:36:23,777 --> 00:36:26,158
and the reason why it's different,

743
00:36:26,578 --> 00:36:28,178
but you know, different players have a different experience,

744
00:36:28,678 --> 00:36:31,499
even though, you know, it's all just basically

745
00:36:31,519 --> 00:36:34,859
a bunch of linear stories, is because their experience,

746
00:36:34,979 --> 00:36:35,980
let's see, is that showing there?

747
00:36:36,040 --> 00:36:37,360
Yep, okay.

748
00:36:37,880 --> 00:36:40,821
That vertical line is their experience of the story

749
00:36:40,941 --> 00:36:42,041
at any given moment, right?

750
00:36:42,301 --> 00:36:43,321
As they go left to right.

751
00:36:43,661 --> 00:36:44,961
But all those events,

752
00:36:45,702 --> 00:36:47,543
These are all kicked off at different times,

753
00:36:48,044 --> 00:36:50,806
so the slice that you're experiencing

754
00:36:50,946 --> 00:36:52,027
is different for different players.

