00:43:20,406 --> 00:43:21,906
and now I just wanted to talk a little bit about

884
00:43:22,187 --> 00:43:24,667
like a bigger framework for making your own original games.

885
00:43:26,621 --> 00:43:30,866
So last year I felt like my life was really stuck,

886
00:43:32,188 --> 00:43:36,874
and I felt like maybe I'm addicted to making games.

887
00:43:37,975 --> 00:43:39,877
Maybe I need to investigate that

888
00:43:39,938 --> 00:43:41,039
and stop it for a little while.

889
00:43:41,800 --> 00:43:43,101
I just spent all my time doing it.

890
00:43:45,811 --> 00:43:48,332
And I felt like my life might be off track.

891
00:43:49,272 --> 00:43:52,354
And I read this book called Designing Your Life.

892
00:43:53,574 --> 00:43:57,816
It was actually written by one of the co-founders of EA.

893
00:43:58,916 --> 00:44:01,958
And they're two Stanford professors.

894
00:44:01,978 --> 00:44:04,779
And in this book, they talk a lot about this concept

895
00:44:04,819 --> 00:44:06,239
of a wicked problem.

896
00:44:07,391 --> 00:44:11,036
And they talk about how people's lives are actually wicked problems.

897
00:44:11,617 --> 00:44:15,362
And these are problems that are highly resistant to solving.

898
00:44:15,863 --> 00:44:18,446
In fact, maybe there is no solving of a wicked problem.

899
00:44:20,188 --> 00:44:22,091
Because our lives certainly cannot be solved.

900
00:44:22,331 --> 00:44:24,995
They can only become subjectively better or worse.

901
00:44:27,141 --> 00:44:29,002
So I was reading about these wicked problems,

902
00:44:29,583 --> 00:44:31,204
and here are their main characteristics

903
00:44:31,244 --> 00:44:32,305
that they talk about.

904
00:44:32,645 --> 00:44:35,447
Now keep in mind, you know, wicked problems,

905
00:44:35,687 --> 00:44:37,949
they're not saying it's only life, people's lives.

906
00:44:37,969 --> 00:44:40,431
They're also saying, you know, nuclear weapons,

907
00:44:40,711 --> 00:44:45,254
homelessness, you know, poverty, you know, climate change.

908
00:44:45,495 --> 00:44:46,796
These are all wicked problems.

909
00:44:47,156 --> 00:44:48,097
So what do they say about them?

910
00:44:49,097 --> 00:44:51,619
They say they're not understood until after

911
00:44:51,659 --> 00:44:54,782
the formulation of a solution, okay?

912
00:44:56,305 --> 00:44:57,186
You don't know when you're done.

913
00:44:57,466 --> 00:44:58,687
They say there's no stopping point.

914
00:44:59,947 --> 00:45:01,368
So it's not solved.

915
00:45:02,188 --> 00:45:03,729
Solutions are not right or wrong.

916
00:45:06,691 --> 00:45:09,412
Each problem is essentially novel and unique.

917
00:45:12,994 --> 00:45:15,515
And every potential solution is a one-shot operation,

918
00:45:15,695 --> 00:45:17,536
which means you can't ever get better at it.

919
00:45:18,097 --> 00:45:18,997
There's no trial and error.

920
00:45:22,000 --> 00:45:25,283
And there's no body of existing solutions out there,

921
00:45:25,723 --> 00:45:28,525
unlike if you're building bridges or highways

922
00:45:28,605 --> 00:45:31,447
or skyscrapers, there's all this engineering work out there.

923
00:45:31,468 --> 00:45:32,849
You can just go look up solutions.

924
00:45:33,369 --> 00:45:34,590
Wicked problems don't have these things.

925
00:45:34,610 --> 00:45:36,912
So then I thought, this sounds kind of familiar.

926
00:45:36,932 --> 00:45:39,754
This is pretty much exactly like making any original game.

927
00:45:40,814 --> 00:45:43,136
And I realized that actually, original games,

928
00:45:43,516 --> 00:45:45,838
making original games are original problems.

929
00:45:46,158 --> 00:45:47,740
I mean, they're wicked problems.

930
00:45:49,547 --> 00:45:52,028
And we have to think about them in a completely different way

931
00:45:52,068 --> 00:45:53,709
than any other type of problem solving.

932
00:45:55,570 --> 00:45:57,771
So each original game is unique.

933
00:45:59,252 --> 00:46:00,173
There's no end point.

934
00:46:01,714 --> 00:46:02,514
It's never solved.

935
00:46:03,795 --> 00:46:04,855
Again, no trial and error.

936
00:46:06,917 --> 00:46:08,177
And there's no existing solutions.

937
00:46:09,478 --> 00:46:11,920
So this is the whole idea of being in the jungle.

938
00:46:12,999 --> 00:46:15,642
This is not knowing what you're making,

939
00:46:15,802 --> 00:46:19,065
and yet you still have to go ahead and make progress anyways.

940
00:46:19,085 --> 00:46:23,730
There's another quote that I really liked.

941
00:46:27,654 --> 00:46:28,716
And I think that's really true.

942
00:46:29,516 --> 00:46:31,599
Games are insanely complex.

943
00:46:31,679 --> 00:46:33,821
